\begin_layout Standard
The van der Pol oscillator is a model of an electric circuit with a triode
 valve (see Fig.
 1, left).
 In this circuit, negative resistance for low currents turns into positive
 resistance for larger currents.
 The same model is relevant for wind-induced oscillations of buildings due
 to vortex shedding and for aerodynamic flutter.
 The model is noted for reproducing experimentally observed relaxation oscillati
ons.
 These nonlinear periodic oscillations are composed of repeated fast transitions
 between two slowly evolving states, as shown in Fig.
 1, right.
 
\end_layout

