\begin_layout Standard
The non-dimensional form of the van der Pol equation is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\ddot{x}+\mu\left(x^{2}-1\right)\dot{x}+x=\beta p(t),\qquad x\in\mathbb{R},\label{eq:vdp}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu\gg1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta\geq0$
\end_inset

 are parameters, and 
\begin_inset Formula $p(t)$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

-periodic external forcing term.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Show that for small enough 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta>0$
\end_inset

, eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:vdp"

\end_inset

 has a small-amplitude, unstable, 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

-periodic orbit.
 (
\emph on
Hint
\emph default
: use a Poincare map argument)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Consider now the unforced van der Pol equation with 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta=0.$
\end_inset

 Prove that for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu\gg1$
\end_inset

 large enough, the system 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:vdp"

\end_inset

 has solutions of the type shown on the right in Fig.
 1.
 (
\emph on
Hint
\emph default
: Introduce the fast time 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau=\mu t$
\end_inset

 and the new variable 
\begin_inset Formula $y=x^{\prime}+x^{3}/3-x$
\end_inset

, where prime denotes differentiation with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

.
 Analyze the resulting first-order system of differential equations for
 
\begin_inset Formula $(x,y)$
\end_inset

 as a perturbation of the formal zero limit of the small parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon=1/\mu^{2}$
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

